Abstract
This is the code for an empirical risk analysis and comparative analysis of Large Language Models (LLMs). Since there are insufficient resources to protect against all possible threats across the life cycle, systems builders need to take a risk management approach and prioritize across the high risk cases (e.g., risk of LLMs being used to create weapons of mass destruction) and focus on the most likely attack vectors by adversaries. MITRE’s [2023] ATLAS is a valuable public resource for defenders to maintain awareness of the emerging threat actors and attack patterns against AI systems as well as the MIT inci-dentdatabase.ai.
1.	Risk Measurement Framework
While verification and validation methods have been sug-gested in the literature for particular assets at particular stages, previous work has not comprehensively applied assessment across the full life cycle. Our quantitative risk approach (See 
Figure 1) measures Risk as a product of the Threat, Vulnera-bilities, and Consequences in each stage of the life cycle such that R = f(T x V x C), where T is a measure of the frequency and average severity of attack [Strom et al. 2020] against the assets exemplified in a prior publication [anonymous submitted], V is measured by the vulnerability severity [MITRE 2026], and C is the severity of the consequences, with each variable normal-ized zero (none) to 1 (highest). Thus if there is no threat or no vulnerability or no consequence, the risk is zero. In contrast, a high degree of threat, vulnerability, and consequence will yield very high risk. Each of the consequence categories captured in section 3 of Anonymous [submitted] detail associated quan-titative measures of harms. While some of harms are readily quantified financially (e.g., $1.5B to authors for pirated books [Ortutay 2025], $25M extortion from a deep fake [Chen and Magramo 2024]), others are qualitative (e.g., user frustration, loss of reputation) and need to be converted to quantitative form (e.g., loss of revenue from service delays, reduction in stock price). Moreover, the refined weighted risk calculus shown in the bottom of Figure 1 enables the weighting of multiple threat, vulnerability or consequence metrics. For example, this can include a vulnerability measure that is a blending weighting of the known percentage of jailbreaks, hallucinations, and denial of service exploits. Analogously, the consequences of these same vulnerabilities can be measured and weighted based on the model use case (e.g., a high risk use case may have higher consequences for a failure). This quan-titative approach enables defenders to identify the greatest risks in the life cycle, by type of harms and by asset, in order to rationally allocate mitigation investments. 


                  R = T x V x C
Risk (R) = Threat (T) × Vulnerability (V) × Consequence (C)  where:
T = Threat likelihood from 0 to 1 (e.g., annual incident frequency normalized by severity from incidentdatabase.ai, alternatively ATLAS.mitre.org).
V = Vulnerability severity (e.g., jailbreak %, hallucination %, uptime %).
C = Consequence weight (e.g., for high-risk use case, C=1.0 for jailbreak and hallucination, 0.8 for latency, 1 for significant harm).

Or a Weighted Risk Calculus for a particular model version that takes weighted summs
of measure metrics for T, V, and C, averages each, then multiplies them. 


